I made a tool to stack images from my phone using Hyper.sh over the weekend. It takes a video, converts it to frames, aligns the frames to avoid shake/drift and averages them to create an interesting smoothing effect.

This photo was based on a short video clip I took while running to work.

Previously I needed to use Photoshop to make these images up - I've made that accessible from my phone; in the spirit of mobile photography and the best camera is the one you have with you etc etc.

I also wrote a blog post about this...
.
.
.

Putney bridge again, but this time it's the last in a while. Taken en-route to Euston to catch the sleeper train to Inverness. #picoftheday #goodbyelondon
It was a lovely morning, fast forward a few hours and we're back to doom & gloom. I got caught out and left with this rather boring telephoto test shot as my 'highlight' of the day.

Tried to take a picture of a train again. Interestingly, the camera's captured it with a skew that we don't see. That black line should be vertical. 
Thought it made for a nice abstract one; maybe it's just junk.

This car hasn't featured on my Instagram since the beginning of last year. I've taken it's photo three times since then but never thought them interesting enough to post.

I walked past it again today on the way to get my haircut and realised that the reflections from the trees where more interesting than anything else I could line up featuring the whole car.

Playing with the manual camera again, waiting around for the 22 bus.
.
.
.
